Reviewed **`src/blog/people/drafts/Susan-Sarandon.md`** with fresh eyes and appended a `FRESH EYES REVIEW (2026-06-28)` block at the bottom. No body edits made.

**The two biggest issues I flagged:**

1. **The Tim Robbins partnership is missing.** He's named three times as scenery (1993 Oscars, Bull Durham, Iraq War) but never as her 23-year partner. They met on the Bull Durham set, raised two sons, and deliberately never married — and her stated reason ("I've always liked the idea of *choosing* to be with somebody") is itself free Type 8 evidence: refusing the institution so nothing sets her terms. A reader who knows her will notice the omission.

2. **The work→activism payoff is dropped.** *Dead Man Walking* is treated only as an irony beat, but playing Sister Helen Prejean is what made her a real death-penalty abolitionist — exactly the protector-role-bleeds-into-cause point the piece is built to make, left unsaid.

I also noted lighter expansion gaps (Lorenzo's Oil and Rocky Horror for a "screen-icon" piece), some over-repetition of the "life was done to her" spine, and called out the strongest things to preserve — the 1993 inner-thought beat, the Trump empathy turn, and the department-store-panic detail.

Sources: [CNN](https://www.cnn.com/2009/SHOWBIZ/Movies/12/23/sarandon.robbins.split/index.html), [AmoMama/AARP](https://news.amomama.com/137880-susan-sarandon-has-a-strong-explanation.html)
